args:
Free of the dungeons, Leif and Cecile meet with
a White Sparrow scout and plan to rendezvous
with the others. Before they set out, Leif again
asks Cecile to join his cause, but her thoughts
are interrupted by Harle's unwanted arrival.
Cecile and Leif have managed to escape their\nprison, but now face a new trial...
LEEEEEEEEEIF! Oh what, you're too good\nfor my Manachew now?! Is that it, mister?!\nHUH?! IS THAT FREAKIN' IT?!
Cecile, please calm down. I merely said\nthat—Mmmmrrrf?!
Eat up, you! The captain of the White\nSparrows has no business being scrawny!
Oh yeah, there's the stuff. Nothing beats\nthat ol' Manachew flavor...
(We ran straight from our cell to the\nnearest market stall selling these rocks,\nand she has been eating them since.)
(Cecile claims they calm one down, but I\nfeel like I'm babysitting a kid who's had\ntoo much sugar!)
You're not chewing, Leif. More chewing!\nMove those molars!
I am just, er...savoring the taste.
Well? It feels good to chew it, huh?\nReal pick-me-up.
(I can't say I feel any different at all...\nHow can she manage to get into that state\njust from chewing on these...?)
Ugh, I can't believe I was all up in your\ngrill like that. I'm going to go crawl into a\nhole now. So long, sunlight! Farewell, sky!
Don't worry about it. I know you were just\nhappy to get some more Manachew after\ngoing without.
Though I am glad to see you calmer,\nbecause we need to craft a plan to\nescape this place before—
A member of the White Sparrows.\nFredrick, what are you doing here?
After we got separated, we split our force.\nOne group returned to New Alberia, while\nthe other was to rescue you.
Once we learned the Church had taken you\nprisoner, I infiltrated Grams in an attempt\nto learn what I could.
I'm sorry to have placed you in such peril.
Please, Captain, follow me. The others\nhave secured a route through the woods\neast of here.
The rescue squad is waiting past these\nwoods at the border. Let us make haste\nbefore anyone detects your escape.
Leif, so...is it really all right for me to\ncome with you?
You are always welcome in my company,\nCecile—not to mention that you would be\nin mortal peril if you returned to Grams.
But I renounced the knighthood and took\nup as a mercenary. The Sparrows have\nno reason to trouble themselves for me.
Neither did you need to help me, yet you\ndid. Consider this my way of balancing\nthe scales, if you like.
Oh. Well, sure. That makes sense, I guess.
Forgive me for asking this of you again,\nCecile, but are you absolutely certain you\nwon't join our cause in New Alberia?
I still think of you as a trusted friend,\nand it would gladden me beyond words\nto have you as an ally once more.
I...I can't, Leif. I'm so sorry, but I can't.\nGoing back to that life? Being a knight?\nI don't even have the right.
Then don't go back—go forward.\nBegin a NEW life.
You mean start over? Just like that?
I know the loss of King Aurelius still\nweighs heavy on your soul. I know you\nblame yourself for his demise.
But that is not your responsibility alone—\nit is a loss shared equally by all who once\nwore the proud colors of the royal guard.
I believe we all have equal claim to move\nforward now, and you are no exception.
If you have any desire to live as a knight\nagain but simply feel you aren't allowed,\nnow is the time to dispel such notions.
You intervened to help me without a\nthought for your own skin, so I know you\nremain a decent person inside.
And I know you can again walk the knightly\npath you once spoke of with such pride.
So join me, Cecile! Swear your blade to\na good and true regent, and fight for the\nsake of the people once more!
BLARGH! Oh, uh...sorry about that. I just\ncouldn't help starting to fade away there...
Your lofty talk was so dazzling, I came\nclose to melting under its light.
Yeah, because your words were... Ugh.\nLook, fancy talk like that is just poison to\na broken lady like me, all right?
Forgive me, Cecile. I had no intention of\ncausing you pain.
Ugh, you're so pure! You're really going\nto double down and go for the killing\nblow like that?
I can but speak plain and say what is\nin my heart.
Do you really think a failed dropout like\nme can start over again?
I am. So let us go together.
(If I'm honest... I want to take his hand.)
(I know I can't keep living like this... I've\nknown for years. But I'd given up dreaming\nthat life could go back to how it was.)
(Maybe this really is my chance to start\nanew... But I'm still not sure I have the\nright to take it.)
If you'd like to go, then by all means.

Of course, that means these fine folk
would lose their lives, but one can't make
an omelet without smashing all the eggs
against the wall, eh?
What, these two? Oh, they're only the start.\nMercenary lives are just so easy and\nexpendable, you know?
Why, if a certain guildhall were to burn\ndown in a tragic fire, I wonder how many\nin Grams would even notice the loss?
I knew you'd renounced the honor of a\nknight, Harle, but I never dreamt you might\ncast aside all humanity along with it!
Oh, come now. I fail to see how this is a\ndifficult decision for her.
Oh, my dear, dear, Leif. Do you not know\nwhat our old friend Cecile actually DID?
Harle, no! Please! Don't say it!
Don't be silly! We three are far too close\nto be keeping secrets from one another.
Besides, you'll feel so much better once\nyou've told him about how you served your\nking by murdering his own people!
